declare(strict_types=1);
echo '<div class="mk-prose">';
echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">Key topics in the history and memory of the 1966 pogroms.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Question of Genocide</h2>';
echo '<p>Whether the 1966 killings constitute genocide under international law is a question of genuine scholarly and political significance. The 1948 UN Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide defines genocide as acts "committed with intent to destroy, in whole or in part, a national, ethnical, racial or religious group." The 1966 killings targeted the Igbo as an ethnic group — this is not disputed. The question is whether there was organized intent to destroy the Igbo as a group, or whether the killings, however terrible, were more localized and less systematically organized than the legal definition requires.</p>';
echo '<p>Scholars who argue for genocide point to: the organized nature of the attacks (lists, coordination across cities), the military\'s participation or acquiescence, the scale of killing, and the subsequent famine policy during the civil war (which continued the destruction of Igbo lives on a massive scale). Scholars who resist the genocide label point to: the eventual end of the killings before the civil war, the Nigerian government\'s reconciliation policy after the war, and the absence of a documented central command ordering extermination.</p>';
echo '<p>What is not disputed: the killings constituted mass atrocity crimes. Whether they meet the technical legal threshold for genocide does not change their moral weight.</p>';
echo '<h2>Eyewitness Accounts</h2>';
echo '<p>The most important sources for the events of 1966 are the accounts of survivors. These accounts — collected by journalists, academics, and community organizations — describe scenes of extraordinary violence: Igbo being pulled from trains and killed, neighborhoods systematically burned, families separated, children killed. The consistency of accounts across different cities and different witnesses gives them significant evidentiary weight.</p>';
echo '<p>Chinua Achebe, who lost close friends and family members in the killings, wrote that the pogrom "was a planned, systematic elimination of a people." His account in <em>There Was a Country</em> (2012) is the most authoritative literary testimony from an Igbo perspective.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Aburi Accord — The Road Not Taken</h2>';
echo '<p>In January 1967, Nigerian federal and regional leaders met in Aburi, Ghana, at the invitation of the Ghanaian military government. They signed an accord providing for a loose confederation — each region would have substantial autonomy while sharing certain federal functions. The Aburi Accord was widely welcomed in the Eastern Region as a framework that could keep Nigeria together while protecting Igbo interests. It was repudiated by the federal government within weeks, under pressure from British advisers, senior civil servants, and representatives of other regions who feared eastern Nigeria would have too much power under the confederal arrangement.</p>';
echo '<p>The failure of Aburi is the critical juncture: had the accord been implemented, the Biafran war might have been avoided. Its repudiation made secession appear to the Igbo as the only remaining option for security after the pogroms had demonstrated the Nigerian state\'s inability or unwillingness to protect them.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Role of the British Government</h2>';
echo '<p>Declassified British government documents released from the 1990s onward have shed significant light on British knowledge of and response to the 1966 killings. Key findings:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>The British High Commission in Lagos had detailed, accurate reports of the scale and organized nature of the killings within weeks of their occurrence</li>';
echo '<li>The British government chose not to publicly condemn the killings or call for accountability</li>';
echo '<li>British policy was explicitly oriented toward preserving Nigerian unity — partly for strategic reasons (the Cold War context) and partly for commercial reasons (British Petroleum and Shell had enormous oil interests in Nigeria)</li>';
echo '<li>British officials actively discouraged international pressure for humanitarian intervention during the subsequent civil war and famine</li>';
echo '</ul>';
echo '<p>The British government\'s role in enabling the 1966 atrocities and the subsequent war through silence, arms supply, and diplomatic cover remains a subject of historical and moral accountability that has never been adequately addressed.</p>';
echo '<h2>Memory and Commemoration</h2>';
echo '<p>The 1966 pogroms are commemorated annually by Igbo communities, particularly on May 30 (Biafra Remembrance Day), which marks the declaration of Biafran independence as a response to the killings. The Nigerian government has no official commemoration of the 1966 victims. No memorial exists in Abuja or any northern city. The contrast with how other nations remember their mass atrocity events is stark.</p>';
echo '<p>For many Igbo people, the lack of acknowledgment, apology, or accountability for the 1966 killings is not a historical grievance but a present injury — evidence that the Nigerian state still does not regard Igbo lives as equally valued, still does not consider the perpetrators of mass murder against Igbo people as having committed a crime requiring justice. This unresolved injustice is a significant driver of continued Igbo political discontent, IPOB\'s growth, and the persistence of separatist sentiment.</p>';
